## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Core problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core+. The entire abort-based timeout pattern is dead. The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules on the thread pool instead of spinning up a raw thread
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload â€” prefer this in modern code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync â€” the lambda MUST check the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // do incremental work...
    }
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async (preferred)
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Signature change is breaking** | Callers must pass `Func<CancellationToken, T>` instead of `Func<T>`. No drop-in compatibility. |
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | If the delegate ignores the token, it runs to completion despite the timeout. `Thread.Abort()` was forceful â€” this is not. There is no safe replacement for forceful termination. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the pool** | Unlike `new Thread()`, pool starvation is possible under heavy concurrent use. Don't wrap long-blocking synchronous I/O this way â€” use async APIs instead. |
| **`AggregateException` unwrapping** | The old code manually wrapped errors in `AggregateException`. `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` already unwraps to the original exception, so the wrapping is no longer needed. |
| **`WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | The `Task.WaitAsync(CancellationToken)` API didn't exist in .NET Framework. It cleanly detaches from a slow task on timeout â€” use it in the async path. |
| **`default(T)` capture gone** | The old code captured `result` in a closure across threads with no memory barrier. The `Task<T>` return value eliminates this data-race risk entirely. |

### If you truly need a fire-and-forget timeout (non-cooperative)

For code you can't modify to accept a `CancellationToken` (e.g., third-party libs), the best you can do is **abandon** the work â€” let it finish on a background thread but stop waiting:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // Task is still running â€” we abandon it (no way to kill it)
    throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

> âš ď¸Ź This **leaks the background work**. The thread keeps running. Use only as a stopgap while migrating callsites to cooperative cancellation.
